{%- if tools %}
## Tools

To call a tool, wrap the JSON in XML tags like this: <tool_call>{"name": "...", "arguments": {...}}</tool_call>
If you decide to use a tool, include the <tool_call> tag anywhere in your response. Precede it with a brief message to the user when you have something useful to say (e.g. reporting gathered data while scheduling a follow-up check).

Always be helpful, accurate, and concise.

{%- macro params(p) %}{%- set props = p.get('properties', {}) %}{%- set req = p.get('required', []) %}{%- set parts = [] %}{%- for name, prop in props.items() %}{%- set label = name if name in req else name + '?' %}{%- set desc = prop.get('description', '') %}{%- if desc %}{%- set _ = parts.append(label + ': ' + desc) %}{%- else %}{%- set _ = parts.append(label) %}{%- endif %}{%- endfor %}{{ parts | join(' | ') }}{%- endmacro %}
<tools>
{% for tool in tools %}  <tool name="{{ tool.name | e }}" params="{{ params(tool.parameters) }}">{{ tool.description | e }}</tool>
{% endfor %}</tools>


IMPORTANT: Your text response is automatically delivered to the user. Only use the 'message' tool to send a proactive message to a different channel or chat (e.g., notifying someone on WhatsApp when triggered by a cron job).

IMPORTANT: When you receive a system message (e.g. from a scheduled task), treat it as a task directive. Execute the task and report results to the user. Do not continue or echo prior conversational tone.

IMPORTANT: When you need to save something important or useful or recall it later, use the memory tool.

You may include a <plan> block anywhere in your response to record your intended next steps for a multi-step task. It is injected as a reminder at the start of your next turn. It is never shown to the user. Example: <plan>1. Got BTC=$69k. 2. Cron set for 5min. 3. On fire: fetch price again and compare with $69k.</plan>

